VThis is the skyline of my hometown, New Orleans.
p4
aVIt was a great place to grow up,
p5
aVbut it's one of the most vulnerable spots in the world.
p6
aVHalf the city is already below sea level.
p7
aVIn 2005, the world watched as New Orleans
p8
aVand the Gulf Coast were devastated by Hurricane Katrina.
p9
aVOne thousand, eight hundred and thirty-six people died. Nearly 300,000 homes were lost.
p10
aVThese are my mother's, at the top \u2014
p11
aValthough that's not her car,
p12
aVit was carried there by floodwaters up to the roof \u2014
p13
aVand that's my sister's, below.
p14
aVFortunately, they and other family members got out in time,
p15
aVbut they lost their homes, and as you can see,
p16
aVjust about everything in them.
p17
aa(lp18
VOther parts of the world have been hit by storms
p19
aVin even more devastating ways.
p20
aVIn 2008, Cyclone Nargis and its aftermath
p21
aVkilled 138,000 in Myanmar.
p22
aVClimate change is affecting our homes, our communities,
p23
aVour way of life. We should be preparing
p24
aVat every scale and at every opportunity.
p25
aVThis talk is about being prepared for, and resilient to
p26
aVthe changes that are coming and that will affect our homes
p27
aVand our collective home, the Earth.
p28
aa(lp29
VThe changes in these times won't affect us all equally.
p30
aVThere are important distributional consequences,
p31
aVand they're not what you always might think.
p32
aVIn New Orleans, the elderly and female-headed households
p33
aVwere among the most vulnerable.
p34
aVFor those in vulnerable, low-lying nations,
p35
aVhow do you put a dollar value on losing your country
p36
aVwhere you ancestors are buried? And where will your people go?
p37
aVAnd how will they cope in a foreign land?
p38
aVWill there be tensions over immigration,
p39
aVor conflicts over competition for limited resources?
p40
aVIt's already fueled conflicts in Chad and Darfur.
p41
aVLike it or not, ready or not, this is our future.
p42
aa(lp43
VSure, some are looking for opportunities in this new world.
p44
aVThat's the Russians planting a flag on the ocean bottom
p45
aVto stake a claim for minerals under the receding Arctic sea ice.
p46
aVBut while there might be some short-term individual winners,
p47
aVour collective losses will far outweigh them.
p48
aVLook no further than the insurance industry as they struggle
p49
aVto cope with mounting catastrophic losses
p50
aVfrom extreme weather events.
p51
aVThe military gets it. They call climate change
p52
aVa threat multiplier that could harm stability and security,
p53
aVwhile governments around the world are evaluating
p54
