aa(lp133
VThird, adapting to rising seas.
p134
aVSea level rise threatens coastal ecosystems, agriculture,
p135
aVeven major cities. This is what one to two meters
p136
aVof sea level rise looks like in the Mekong Delta.
p137
aVThat's where half of Vietnam's rice is grown.
p138
aVInfrastructure is going to be affected.
p139
aVAirports around the world are located on the coast.
p140
aVIt makes sense, right? There's open space,
p141
aVthe planes can take off and land without worrying about
p142
aVcreating noise or avoiding tall buildings.
p143
aVHere's just one example, San Francisco Airport,
p144
aVwith 16 inches or more of flooding.
p145
aVImagine the staggering cost of protecting
p146
aVthis vital infrastructure with levees.
p147
aVBut there might be some changes in store
p148
aVthat you might not imagine. For example,
p149
aVplanes require more runway for takeoff
p150
aVbecause the heated, less dense air, provides for less lift.
p151
aVSan Francisco is also spending 40 million dollars
p152
aVto rethink and redesign its water and sewage treatment,
p153
aVas water outfall pipes like this one can be flooded with seawater,
p154
aVcausing backups at the plant, harming the bacteria
p155
aVthat are needed to treat the waste.
p156
aVSo these outfall pipes have been retrofitted
p157
aVto shut seawater off from entering the system.
